---
import CaseLayout from '../layouts/CaseLayout.astro';
import ReaderColumn from '../components/reader/ReaderColumn.astro';
import Hero from '../components/reader/Hero.astro';
import MetaRow from '../components/reader/MetaRow.astro';
import Section from '../components/reader/Section.astro';
import SectionLabel from '../components/reader/SectionLabel.astro';
import H2 from '../components/reader/H2.astro';
import Lead from '../components/reader/Lead.astro';
import Body from '../components/reader/Body.astro';
import Callout from '../components/reader/Callout.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/reader/PullQuote.astro';
import MarginRef from '../components/reader/MarginRef.astro';
import Hr from '../components/reader/Hr.astro';
import Outcome from '../components/reader/Outcome.astro';
import EndRow from '../components/reader/EndRow.astro';
import ImgSlot from '../components/reader/ImgSlot.astro';
---

<CaseLayout
  title="Fleet View — Sivanesh TV"
  caseNum="02"
  caseName="Fleet View"
  description="Building Fleet View — a real-time operations dashboard for managing multiple drone fleets across sites, missions, and operators at FlytBase."
  ogImage="/assets/fleet/fleet-hero.png"
  jsonLd={{
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'CreativeWork',
    name: 'Fleet View',
    description: 'Building Fleet View — a real-time operations dashboard for managing multiple drone fleets across sites, missions, and operators at FlytBase.',
    url: 'https://sivanesh.tv/fleet',
    author: { '@type': 'Person', name: 'Sivanesh TV', url: 'https://sivanesh.tv' },
    keywords: 'product design, fleet management, drone operations, dashboard design',
  }}
>
  <Fragment slot="reader">
    <ReaderColumn>
      <Hero
        eyebrow="case study · 02"
        title='Fleet <em>View.</em>'
        sub="Designing the interface that made it possible for one operator to safely manage an entire drone fleet — and giving regulators the evidence they needed to allow it."
      />

      <MetaRow items={[
        { k: 'Role', v: 'Product designer' },
        { k: 'Year', v: '2025' },
        { k: 'Scope', v: 'End-to-end Product design' },
        { k: 'Tools', v: 'Figma · Claude · Lovable' },
      ]} />

      <ImgSlot variant="wide"
        src="/assets/fleet/fleet-hero.png"
        alt="Fleet View — multiple active drones, live video feeds, map and alert panel in live operation"
        cap="Fleet View — 8 drones, 2 sites, 13 alerts · live"
        capMeta="the interface"
      />

      <!-- § 01 Context -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The project" num="§ 01" />
        <H2>Fleet View is the <em>command environment</em> for operators running many drones at once.</H2>
        <Lead>The business problem was simple: more drones, same number of pilots. The design problem was harder — <em>how do you keep one person genuinely safe across ten simultaneous flights?</em></Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>As FlytBase deployments scaled — more docks, fewer pilots per site, alarm integrations firing at any hour — operators found themselves responsible for fleets their existing interface wasn't built for. Fleet View was the product response: a dedicated environment where one operator could observe, manage, and execute safety controls across every active flight simultaneously.</p>
          <p>And because CAA bodies were beginning to grant <strong>One-to-Many waivers</strong> — permitting a single licensed pilot to command multiple armed drones concurrently — the design also had to function as <em>regulatory evidence</em> of adequate situational awareness. The interface wasn't just a product. It was part of a safety case.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <!-- § 02 The challenge -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The challenge" num="§ 02" />
        <PullQuote>Two different people. Completely different needs. One interface that couldn't afford to <em>fail either of them.</em></PullQuote>
        <Body>
          <p>Every ROC (Remote Operations Centre) runs on two roles, and they use Fleet View completely differently.</p>
          <p>The <strong>pilot</strong> is the one in the seat — trained to fly, certified to command, responsible when something happens. They dispatch drones, respond to alarms, and take direct control under pressure. Their need is depth: the ability to go all the way into <em>one</em> drone without losing awareness of the others.</p>
          <p>The <strong>manager</strong> watches the whole operation. Fleet state, pilot assignments, brief telemetry across every drone in the air, shift performance, regulatory logs. Most of the time they're observing, not commanding — until a critical moment demands otherwise, and then they need to step into what the pilot is doing without friction.</p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p>One interface. Two mental models. Zero tolerance for losing sight of a drone — because at any moment, either role might need to <em>step into</em> what the other was doing.</p></Callout>

        <div class="personas">
          <div class="persona persona-pilot">
            <div class="persona-tape"></div>
            <div class="persona-role">Role · 01</div>
            <div class="persona-head">
              <img class="persona-avatar" src="/assets/fleet/persona-pilot.jpg" alt="Pilot persona" />
              <div class="persona-ident">
                <div class="persona-name">The pilot.</div>
                <div class="persona-sub">In the seat. In command.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="persona-section">
              <div class="persona-lbl">— primary need —</div>
              <div class="persona-need">Depth without losing awareness.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="persona-section">
              <div class="persona-lbl">— what they do —</div>
              <ul class="persona-list">
                <li>Dispatch drones to incidents</li>
                <li>Respond to alarms in real time</li>
                <li>Take direct control when needed</li>
                <li>Execute safety commands under pressure</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="persona-section">
              <div class="persona-lbl">— the pressure —</div>
              <p class="persona-pressure">Every alarm has a countdown. Every drone they lose sight of is liability they can't recover.</p>
            </div>
            <blockquote class="persona-quote persona-quote-pilot">
              "I need to go deep — <em>without going blind.</em>"
            </blockquote>
          </div>

          <div class="persona persona-manager">
            <div class="persona-tape"></div>
            <div class="persona-role persona-role-manager">Role · 02</div>
            <div class="persona-head">
              <img class="persona-avatar" src="/assets/fleet/persona-manager.jpg" alt="Manager persona" />
              <div class="persona-ident">
                <div class="persona-name">The manager.</div>
                <div class="persona-sub">Watching the operation.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="persona-section">
              <div class="persona-lbl">— primary need —</div>
              <div class="persona-need">Breadth without losing precision.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="persona-section">
              <div class="persona-lbl">— what they do —</div>
              <ul class="persona-list">
                <li>Oversee the full ROC operation</li>
                <li>Track fleet state and pilot load</li>
                <li>Audit regulatory logs</li>
                <li>Step in when a pilot needs support</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="persona-section">
              <div class="persona-lbl">— the pressure —</div>
              <p class="persona-pressure">Accountability for every drone. A CAA evaluator could pull their logs at any moment.</p>
            </div>
            <blockquote class="persona-quote persona-quote-manager">
              "I need to see everything — <em>without staring at any one thing.</em>"
            </blockquote>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="personas-footer">
          At any moment, <em>either role might need to step into what the other was doing.</em>
          <span>One interface · Two mental models · Zero ambiguity</span>
        </p>
      </Section>

      <Hr />

      <!-- § 03 The central decision -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The central decision" num="§ 03" />
        <H2>Group, don't <em>filter.</em></H2>
        <Lead>Standard data tables let you filter rows out. In a drone fleet dashboard, that's the wrong instinct.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>The obvious move when an interface gets crowded is to let the user filter — show me only the drones at Site A, hide the idle ones, only show alerts. But filtering <em>removes drones from awareness</em>. And in a regulated environment, that's exactly what a CAA evaluator does not want to see. An operator can't claim situational awareness over a drone they filtered off their screen.</p>
          <p>So we took a different approach: <strong>grouping instead of filtering</strong>. Every drone stays visible. Every drone stays in the operator's field of attention. Grouping lets the operator collapse and expand without ever losing a drone from the count. Armed drones? Grouped, but the group count and status indicator remain prominent. Idle fleet? Collapsed, but the number of idle drones is explicit at the header level.</p>
        </Body>
        <Callout><p>Filtering was our first instinct. It took a conversation with the regulatory team — about what <em>losing visibility</em> actually means in a waiver submission — to understand why we couldn't ship it. A filtered drone isn't an organised drone. It's a drone the operator is no longer accountable for. And in this domain, <em>accountability is non-negotiable</em>.</p></Callout>
        <MarginRef jump="grouping">↗ see the grouping architecture</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/fleet/fleet-grouping.png"
          alt="Fleet View grouping architecture — drones grouped by state, collapsed groups showing count"
          cap="Grouping preserves awareness — filtering destroys it"
          capMeta="the rule"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 04 The interface -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The interface" num="§ 04" />
        <H2>Every panel talking to every other panel. <em>Always.</em></H2>
        <Lead>Fleet View is organised around four simultaneous panels — list, map, video wall, alerts — but the interface's real principle is what happens <em>between</em> them.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>The <strong>list</strong> is the spine: every drone, grouped by state. The <strong>map</strong> shows where they are. The <strong>video wall</strong> tiles live feeds by group priority. The <strong>alerts panel</strong> surfaces everything that needs attention, sorted by severity.</p>
          <p>Select a drone in any one of these panels and the other three respond. Click an alert and the affected drone highlights on the map, its video border lights up, and the list scrolls to it. Zoom in on a drone in the map and the list row highlights. The state is shared. The selection is shared. The four panels aren't four views of a fleet — they're four facets of one synchronised awareness.</p>
          <p>This is what makes <em>one</em> interface function for both pilot and manager. A pilot going deep on one drone still sees the fleet in their peripheral vision. A manager watching the full operation can step into any pilot's workspace with one click — same state, same highlight, same context. The depth of focus is up to the operator. The fleet never disappears.</p>
        </Body>

        <Callout><p><em>App drawer hosts two kinds of tools.</em> Layer 0 squeezes the body to make space. Layer 1 overlays it without displacement. Never both at once. The operator always knows whether their workspace shrank or stayed.</p></Callout>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/fleet/fleet-interface.png"
          alt="Fleet View four-panel interface — drone list, map, video wall, and alerts panel all synchronised"
          cap="Four panels, synchronised state · every drone always visible"
          capMeta="the layout"
        />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 05 Alarm dispatch -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="The alarm flow" num="§ 05" />
        <H2>The hardest scenario in fleet ops — designed as a <em>first-class workflow.</em></H2>
        <Lead>A critical alarm fires. Eight drones are already in the air. The interface has to tell the operator what happened, show them where, and give them a response path — without losing the other seven.</Lead>
        <Body>
          <p>Clicking the alarm — from the panel or the map — opens the response workspace. The card shows what fired, when, a unique alarm ID for audit, and the <em>automation state</em>: was a drone pre-assigned to this alarm, or does the operator pick one now? That one detail changes the whole flow.</p>
        </Body>

        <Callout>
          <p><strong>If the alarm is set to <em>Auto</em>.</strong> A drone was already assigned to this alarm condition. It's already flying to the location. The operator's job is to <em>monitor and supervise</em> — watch the dispatch unfold, step in if conditions change.</p>
          <p><strong>If the alarm is set to <em>Manual</em>.</strong> No drone has been assigned. The operator picks one — configures the flight as a mission or a Go-To-Location, and dispatches. One click sends it.</p>
        </Callout>

        <Body>
          <p>Fleet View gives the operator the full command surface <em>without</em> the piloting surface. Trigger a response, modify an auto-dispatched drone's path, execute safety commands across any selection — all from here. For direct piloting, they enter Cockpit View. That boundary is deliberate: Fleet is where one person commands many; Cockpit is where one person flies one. The manager watching the operation has the same access the pilot does — same alarm card, same dispatch controls, no permission-asking.</p>
        </Body>
        <MarginRef jump="alarm-flow">↗ see the alarm dispatch flow</MarginRef>

        <ImgSlot variant="wide"
          src="/assets/fleet/fleet-alarm.png"
          alt="Fleet View alarm response card — automation state, drone assignment, Mission and GTL configuration"
          cap="Alarm response · Manual path, drone being assigned"
          capMeta="the moment"
        />
      </Section>

      <Hr />

      <!-- § 06 Outcomes -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What it enabled" num="§ 06" />
        <H2>The receipts.</H2>

        <Outcome items={[
          { n: 'Live', l: 'Deployed', d: 'Fleet View shipped as the primary multi-drone interface across FlytBase enterprise deployments, replacing the multi-tab, multi-monitor workarounds operators had built themselves.' },
          { n: 'CAA', l: 'Evidence-ready', d: 'The grouping architecture became part of the evidence case for One-to-Many waivers — proof that an operator cannot accidentally remove an armed drone from their field of awareness.' },
          { n: '1→N', l: 'New operational standard', d: 'One pilot. Multiple armed drones. Full situational awareness. What required multiple operators — or improvised workarounds — became a designed, compliant, scalable workflow.' },
        ]} />
      </Section>

      <!-- § 07 Reflection -->
      <Section>
        <SectionLabel text="What I took away" num="§ 07" />
        <Body>
          <p><strong>Challenging a universal pattern is a product decision, not a design one.</strong> "Grouping not filtering" wasn't a visual choice. It required understanding what filtering would cost in this domain — and being willing to challenge a pattern that works everywhere else. That's a product call, and it had to be made before any interface was designed.</p>
          <p><strong>Design can be regulatory infrastructure.</strong> When a CAA evaluator asks whether an operator has adequate situational awareness, the interface is the answer. Knowing that changed the stakes of every structural decision — the grouping model, the priority hierarchy, the always-visible safety controls all had to work as proof, not just as features.</p>
          <p><strong>The most important moment in a product is the one you design for first.</strong> Building the alarm dispatch workflow as a first-class, integrated flow — not as a side path from the main monitoring view — shaped every subsequent layout and panel decision. Design the hardest moment first. Everything else will fit around it.</p>
        </Body>
      </Section>

      <EndRow note="— end of case · § 02 / 03 —" nextLabel="Next: Asset Management ↗" nextHref="/asset" />
    </ReaderColumn>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="artifacts">
    <!-- §00 HERO — wayfinding -->
    <div class="marker md red artifact" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="-80" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="200" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-8deg);font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:34px;line-height:1.1;color:var(--marker-red)">↓ read straight through</div>
    <div class="marker sm black artifact" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="-40" data-side="right" data-gap="40" data-width="180" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(4deg);font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:18px;line-height:1.1;color:var(--ink)">drag around to<br>explore →</div>

    <!-- §01 PROJECT — dark CAA context card (the regulatory framing) -->
    <div class="context-card artifact" id="obj-caa-context" data-anchor="0" data-anchor-offset="380" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="380" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-2deg);width:380px;padding:24px;background:var(--ink);color:var(--paper);box-shadow:3px 5px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.06),6px 14px 28px rgba(40,35,25,.2)">
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:10px">— CAA context · one-to-many waivers —</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-weight:700;font-size:20px;line-height:1.25;margin-bottom:10px;color:#fdf8ea">This wasn't just a product. It was part of a <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--red)">safety case.</em></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-size:13px;line-height:1.55;color:rgba(253,248,234,.8)">CAAs worldwide were beginning to grant One-to-Many waivers — a single licensed pilot commanding multiple armed drones. Fleet View had to function as <em style="font-style:italic;color:#fdf8ea">evidence</em> that the operator maintained genuine situational awareness across every drone at once.</div>
    </div>

    <!-- §01 — stakes sticky -->
    <div class="sticky artifact" id="obj-stakes" data-anchor="1" data-anchor-offset="240" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="260" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(3deg);width:260px;min-height:180px;padding:22px 20px 18px;font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:500;font-size:20px;line-height:1.35;color:var(--ink);background:var(--yellow);box-shadow:2px 4px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.05),4px 8px 16px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div class="sticky-eyebrow" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:8px">— the operational pressure —</div>
      More drones, <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">same pilots.</em> Alarm integrations firing at any hour. The interface hadn't caught up.
    </div>

    <!-- §02 CHALLENGE — the REAL 4K workaround quote -->
    <div class="sticky pink artifact" id="obj-workaround" data-anchor="1" data-anchor-offset="40" data-side="left" data-gap="60" data-width="300" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(-4deg);width:300px;min-height:180px;padding:22px 20px 18px;font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:500;font-size:20px;line-height:1.35;color:var(--ink);background:#ff8fa3;box-shadow:2px 4px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.05),4px 8px 16px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div class="sticky-eyebrow" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:8px">— observed workaround —</div>
      Some pilots split their 4K monitor into <em style="font-style:normal;color:var(--red);font-weight:700">four sections</em> — separate browsers, separate tabs, one per drone. That's the workflow we were trying to end.
    </div>

    <!-- §03 CENTRAL DECISION — THE principle card -->
    <div class="principle artifact" id="obj-group-not-filter" data-anchor="2" data-anchor-offset="30" data-side="right" data-gap="80" data-width="380" style="position:absolute;transform:rotate(1.5deg);width:380px;padding:32px 32px 28px;background:var(--paper);box-shadow:3px 5px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.06),6px 14px 28px rgba(40,35,25,.2);border:1px solid rgba(40,35,25,.08)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-12px;right:10%;width:90px;height:22px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(3deg);box-shadow:0 2px 6px rgba(40,35,25,.1)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--red);margin-bottom:14px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px"><span>◆</span>the rule the entire case rests on</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-weight:700;font-size:26px;line-height:1.15;letter-spacing:-.02em;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:10px">Grouping, <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--red)">not filtering.</em></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fs);font-size:13px;line-height:1.55;color:var(--ink-2);margin-bottom:14px">Filtering removes drones from awareness — which means removing them from the <em style="font-style:italic;color:var(--ink)">safety case.</em> Grouping collapses them while keeping every drone counted, visible, and auditable.</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:600;font-size:17px;color:var(--ink-3);padding-top:12px;border-top:1px dashed rgba(40,35,25,.18)">— quoted from the PRD</div>
    </div>

    <!-- §03 — grouping diagram with REAL column-based grouping examples -->
    <div class="diagram artifact" id="obj-grouping" data-anchor="2" data-anchor-offset="560" data-side="right" data-gap="60" data-width="460" style="position:absolute;width:460px;transform:rotate(-1deg);padding:24px;background:var(--paper);box-shadow:2px 3px 0 rgba(40,35,25,.04),4px 8px 20px rgba(40,35,25,.18)">
      <div style="position:absolute;top:-10px;left:40%;width:60px;height:20px;background:var(--tape);opacity:.85;transform:rotate(-3deg)"></div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fh);font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:var(--ink);margin-bottom:4px">Column-based grouping</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--ink-3);margin-bottom:16px">— select a column · drones group by its values —</div>
